if(!window.MM) window.MM={};
window.MM['oph_p2_ocular_pharma']=[
  {q:"A patient with acute anterior uveitis is prescribed atropine eye drops primarily to:",o:["Produce cycloplegia and prevent posterior synechiae","Reduce intraocular pressure","Treat bacterial infection","Decrease corneal edema","Improve retinal perfusion"],a:0,e:"Atropine is a potent cycloplegic and mydriatic agent used in anterior uveitis to immobilize the inflamed iris and prevent posterior synechiae formation.<br><br>Cycloplegia also relieves painful ciliary muscle spasm and reduces photophobia. Atropine may produce prolonged mydriasis lasting several days.<br><br>It does not directly treat infection (C) or lower intraocular pressure (B). Corneal edema (D) and retinal perfusion abnormalities (E) are not primary therapeutic targets of atropine.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A glaucoma patient develops worsening wheezing after starting timolol eye drops. Which mechanism explains this complication?",o:["Muscarinic stimulation","Systemic beta-blockade after nasolacrimal absorption","Histamine release","Carbonic anhydrase inhibition","Alpha-1 stimulation"],a:1,e:"Topical timolol may undergo systemic absorption through the nasolacrimal system and produce beta-blocker side effects including bronchospasm and bradycardia.<br><br>This is especially important in patients with asthma or COPD. Punctal occlusion reduces systemic absorption and toxicity.<br><br>Carbonic anhydrase inhibition (D) is the mechanism of acetazolamide and dorzolamide rather than timolol. Alpha-1 stimulation (E) produces mydriasis instead.<br><br><em>(Recall and Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which topical antiglaucoma drug increases uveoscleral aqueous outflow and commonly causes eyelash growth?",o:["Timolol","Acetazolamide","Pilocarpine","Latanoprost","Brimonidine"],a:3,e:"Latanoprost is a prostaglandin analogue that lowers intraocular pressure by increasing uveoscleral outflow of aqueous humor.<br><br>Characteristic side effects include conjunctival hyperemia, increased iris pigmentation, and eyelash growth. It is widely used in primary open-angle glaucoma.<br><br>Timolol (A) decreases aqueous production rather than increasing uveoscleral drainage. Pilocarpine (C) acts mainly through trabecular outflow enhancement.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient undergoing cycloplegic refraction requires a short-acting cycloplegic agent. Which drug is most appropriate?",o:["Atropine","Homatropine","Tropicamide","Pilocarpine","Timolol"],a:2,e:"Tropicamide is a short-acting antimuscarinic agent commonly used for fundoscopy and cycloplegic refraction because recovery occurs relatively quickly.<br><br>It produces mydriasis with minimal prolonged cycloplegia compared with atropine.<br><br>Atropine (A) may produce cycloplegia lasting up to 1<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with bacterial corneal ulcer is started on topical corticosteroids before antibiotic coverage and subsequently deteriorates rapidly. The most likely explanation is:",o:["Steroids suppress local immune response","Steroids increase tear secretion","Steroids increase aqueous production","Steroids induce miosis","Steroids enhance epithelial healing"],a:0,e:"Topical corticosteroids suppress ocular immune responses and may worsen active corneal infection if administered before adequate antimicrobial therapy.<br><br>Infective keratitis may therefore progress rapidly with stromal melting and perforation. Steroids should be used cautiously and only after infection control.<br><br>Steroids do not enhance epithelial healing (E); in fact, they may delay it. Miosis (D) is not their primary pharmacologic effect.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which topical anesthetic is commonly used before tonometry and foreign body removal?",o:["Proparacaine","Pilocarpine","Brimonidine","Phenylephrine","Atropine"],a:0,e:"Proparacaine is a topical ocular anesthetic widely used before procedures such as tonometry, gonioscopy, and corneal foreign body removal.<br><br>It acts by blocking sodium channels and inhibiting nerve impulse conduction in corneal nerves.<br><br>Phenylephrine (D) is a mydriatic agent, while atropine (E) produces cycloplegia rather than local anesthesia.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient treated with pilocarpine most likely experiences which ocular side effect?",o:["Accommodation spasm","Mydriasis","Loss of accommodation","Exophthalmos","Corneal anesthesia"],a:0,e:"Pilocarpine is a muscarinic agonist causing miosis and ciliary muscle contraction. This may produce brow ache and accommodative spasm.<br><br>The drug enhances trabecular aqueous outflow and was historically important in glaucoma management.<br><br>Loss of accommodation (C) occurs with cycloplegic drugs such as atropine. Mydriasis (B) is opposite to pilocarpine's action.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient receiving prolonged topical steroid therapy is at greatest risk for developing:",o:["Posterior subcapsular cataract and glaucoma","Retinoblastoma","Retinal detachment only","Optic nerve glioma","Macular hole"],a:0,e:"Long-term corticosteroid therapy may elevate intraocular pressure and induce posterior subcapsular cataract formation.<br><br>Regular monitoring of intraocular pressure is therefore essential in patients requiring chronic steroid therapy.<br><br>Retinoblastoma (B) and optic nerve glioma (D) are unrelated neoplastic disorders. Macular hole (E) is not a classic steroid complication.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which drug acts by decreasing aqueous humor production through carbonic anhydrase inhibition?",o:["Latanoprost","Pilocarpine","Dorzolamide","Phenylephrine","Tropicamide"],a:2,e:"Dorzolamide is a topical carbonic anhydrase inhibitor that decreases aqueous humor secretion by the ciliary body.<br><br>It is commonly used in glaucoma therapy and may cause local burning sensation or bitter taste.<br><br>Latanoprost (A) increases uveoscleral outflow rather than reducing aqueous production. Pilocarpine (B) enhances trabecular drainage.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient requires pupillary dilation for retinal examination without cycloplegia. Which drug is most appropriate?",o:["Atropine","Tropicamide","Phenylephrine","Pilocarpine","Acetazolamide"],a:2,e:"Phenylephrine is an alpha-1 adrenergic agonist producing mydriasis by stimulating the iris dilator muscle without significant cycloplegia.<br><br>It is commonly combined with tropicamide for fundoscopy.<br><br>Atropine (A) and tropicamide (B) are antimuscarinic agents producing both mydriasis and cycloplegia. Pilocarpine (D) causes miosis.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with acute angle-closure glaucoma is given intravenous mannitol. Its primary therapeutic effect is:",o:["Increasing aqueous production","Osmotic dehydration of vitreous","Stimulating trabecular fibrosis","Producing cycloplegia","Causing miosis"],a:1,e:"Mannitol is an osmotic agent that reduces intraocular pressure by drawing fluid from the vitreous into the bloodstream.<br><br>It is especially useful in acute severe glaucoma requiring rapid pressure reduction.<br><br>Cycloplegia (D) and miosis (E) are not the primary mechanisms of mannitol therapy. Increasing aqueous production (A) would worsen glaucoma.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which drug class is most associated with irreversible iris pigmentation changes in glaucoma patients?",o:["Beta blockers","Prostaglandin analogues","Alpha agonists","Carbonic anhydrase inhibitors","Topical NSAIDs"],a:1,e:"Prostaglandin analogues such as latanoprost may increase melanin deposition within the iris, producing permanent darkening.<br><br>Eyelash thickening and periocular skin pigmentation are additional recognized side effects.<br><br>Beta blockers (A) more commonly produce cardiopulmonary systemic effects rather than iris pigmentation changes.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with corneal abrasion is repeatedly self-administering topical anesthetic drops and develops worsening epithelial defect. The reason is that topical anesthetics:",o:["Accelerate stromal melting","Delay corneal epithelial healing","Increase aqueous humor formation","Produce retinal toxicity only","Cause pupillary block"],a:1,e:"Repeated topical anesthetic use is toxic to the corneal epithelium and delays epithelial regeneration, potentially causing corneal ulceration.<br><br>These agents should never be prescribed for unsupervised prolonged use.<br><br>Pupillary block (E) is unrelated to anesthetic toxicity. Retinal toxicity (D) is not the main complication of excessive topical anesthetic use.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which ocular drug is contraindicated in patients with asthma because of risk of bronchospasm?",o:["Timolol","Latanoprost","Tropicamide","Phenylephrine","Pilocarpine"],a:0,e:"Timolol is a non-selective beta blocker that may cause systemic bronchospasm after topical absorption through the nasolacrimal system.<br><br>Asthmatic patients may therefore develop life-threatening respiratory complications.<br><br>Latanoprost (B) and tropicamide (C) do not commonly produce bronchospasm. Pilocarpine (E) mainly causes ocular parasympathetic effects.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with allergic conjunctivitis is prescribed mast cell stabilizer therapy. Which mechanism best explains its action?",o:["Prevention of mast cell degranulation","Immediate vasoconstriction only","Cycloplegia induction","Carbonic anhydrase inhibition","Muscarinic blockade"],a:0,e:"Mast cell stabilizers prevent release of inflammatory mediators such as histamine from sensitized mast cells in allergic conjunctivitis.<br><br>They are useful prophylactically in recurrent allergic disease but may not provide immediate symptomatic relief.<br><br>Cycloplegia (C) and muscarinic blockade (E) are unrelated pharmacologic actions.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient receiving acetazolamide for glaucoma develops tingling sensations and metabolic acidosis. Which mechanism is responsible?",o:["Alpha-1 blockade","Carbonic anhydrase inhibition","Beta stimulation","Histamine antagonism","Muscarinic activation"],a:1,e:"Acetazolamide inhibits carbonic anhydrase, reducing aqueous humor production but also causing systemic bicarbonate loss and metabolic acidosis.<br><br>Paresthesias, renal stones, and electrolyte imbalance are common side effects.<br><br>Alpha blockade (A) and histamine antagonism (D) are unrelated to acetazolamide pharmacology.<br><br><em>(Recall and Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which route of ocular drug administration provides the highest intraocular drug concentration for endophthalmitis treatment?",o:["Oral","Topical","Subconjunctival","Intravitreal","Retrobulbar"],a:3,e:"Intravitreal injection delivers therapeutic drug concentrations directly into the vitreous cavity and is critical in severe intraocular infections such as endophthalmitis.<br><br>Topical and systemic therapy alone often fail to achieve adequate vitreous levels because of ocular barriers.<br><br>Retrobulbar injections (E) are mainly anesthetic techniques rather than primary antimicrobial delivery methods.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient undergoing fundoscopy develops acute angle-closure glaucoma after mydriatic drops. Which anatomical predisposition most likely existed?",o:["Narrow anterior chamber angle","Deep anterior chamber","High myopia","Vitreous degeneration","Retinal detachment"],a:0,e:"Mydriasis may precipitate pupillary block and acute angle closure in anatomically predisposed eyes with shallow anterior chambers and narrow angles.<br><br>Hypermetropic elderly patients are particularly at risk.<br><br>Deep anterior chambers (B) protect against angle closure rather than predisposing to it. Vitreous degeneration (D) is unrelated.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which topical medication is most appropriate for producing miosis after acute angle-closure glaucoma pressure has been lowered?",o:["Tropicamide","Phenylephrine","Pilocarpine","Atropine","Timolol"],a:2,e:"Pilocarpine causes pupillary constriction and ciliary muscle contraction, helping open the trabecular meshwork and improve aqueous drainage.<br><br>It is useful in angle-closure glaucoma after initial pressure reduction because ischemic iris sphincter may initially respond poorly at extremely high pressures.<br><br>Atropine (D) and tropicamide (A) produce mydriasis, which may worsen angle closure.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient receiving prolonged topical aminoglycoside therapy develops punctate epithelial toxicity. Which drug class most commonly causes this complication?",o:["Aminoglycosides","Prostaglandin analogues","Cycloplegics","Carbonic anhydrase inhibitors","Osmotic agents"],a:0,e:"Topical aminoglycosides such as gentamicin and tobramycin may cause epithelial toxicity and punctate keratopathy with prolonged use.<br><br>Careful monitoring is important in chronic therapy because corneal surface damage may worsen patient discomfort and delay healing.<br><br>Cycloplegics (C) primarily affect pupil and accommodation. Osmotic agents (E) are not associated with epithelial toxicity.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A 68-year-old glaucoma patient develops progressive fatigue, impotence, bradycardia, and depression several months after initiation of topical therapy. Which drug is most likely responsible?",o:["Latanoprost","Timolol","Pilocarpine","Brinzolamide","Phenylephrine"],a:1,e:"Topical timolol may produce significant systemic beta-blockade because ocular medications are absorbed through conjunctival and nasolacrimal mucosa.<br><br>Bradycardia, hypotension, bronchospasm, impotence, fatigue, and depression are classic high-yield adverse effects repeatedly tested in<br><br>Latanoprost (A) mainly causes local cosmetic changes such as iris pigmentation and eyelash growth. Phenylephrine (E) may elevate blood pressure but does not typically produce bradycardia.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient receiving prolonged topical corticosteroid therapy develops elevated intraocular pressure because steroids reduce aqueous outflow through the:",o:["Trabecular meshwork","Canaliculi","Ciliary body epithelium","Vitreous cavity","Choroidal circulation"],a:0,e:"Steroids induce biochemical changes within the trabecular meshwork, increasing resistance to aqueous drainage and causing secondary open-angle glaucoma.<br><br>Steroid responders are particularly susceptible, and prolonged therapy may produce irreversible optic nerve damage if unrecognized.<br><br>Ciliary body epithelium (C) mainly controls aqueous production rather than outflow resistance. Canaliculi (B) are lacrimal drainage structures.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with severe corneal ulcer is prescribed fortified cefazolin and tobramycin eye drops hourly. The rationale for fortified preparations is primarily to:",o:["Increase systemic absorption","Reduce tear secretion","Prevent cataract formation","Achieve therapeutic corneal concentrations","Produce cycloplegia"],a:3,e:"Fortified topical antibiotics are specially concentrated formulations used in severe microbial keratitis to achieve high local bactericidal levels within corneal tissue.<br><br>Standard commercial preparations may be inadequate for deep stromal or aggressive infections such as pseudomonal ulcers.<br><br>Cycloplegia (E) may be added separately but is not the primary reason for fortified antibiotic use. Systemic absorption (A) is not the therapeutic objective.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with chronic open-angle glaucoma develops recurrent allergic follicular conjunctivitis after topical therapy. Which medication is most classically associated with this adverse effect?",o:["Timolol","Acetazolamide","Latanoprost","Brimonidine","Pilocarpine"],a:3,e:"Brimonidine, an alpha-2 adrenergic agonist, commonly causes allergic follicular conjunctivitis during chronic therapy.<br><br>Patients may complain of itching, redness, tearing, and foreign-body sensation after weeks to months of use.<br><br>Timolol (A) more commonly causes systemic cardiopulmonary side effects. Pilocarpine (E) causes brow ache and accommodative spasm rather than follicular allergy.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with acute angle-closure glaucoma receives acetazolamide. Which acid-base disturbance is most likely to occur?",o:["Metabolic alkalosis","Respiratory alkalosis","Metabolic acidosis","Respiratory acidosis","Mixed alkalosis"],a:2,e:"Acetazolamide inhibits renal carbonic anhydrase, causing bicarbonate wasting and metabolic acidosis.<br><br>Paresthesias, renal stones, and hypokalemia are additional high-yield adverse effects. Sulfonamide allergy is an important contraindication.<br><br>Respiratory disturbances (B, D) are not the primary mechanism because acetazolamide acts mainly through renal bicarbonate loss.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with herpetic epithelial keratitis deteriorates after topical steroid therapy because corticosteroids:",o:["Increase stromal hydration only","Promote viral replication","Cause immediate retinal necrosis","Induce acute cataract","Reduce tear osmolarity"],a:1,e:"Topical corticosteroids suppress local immune defense and permit uncontrolled herpes simplex viral replication within the corneal epithelium.<br><br>This may enlarge dendritic ulcers into geographic ulcers with stromal destruction and perforation risk.<br><br>Acute cataract formation (D) does not occur immediately after steroid use. Tear osmolarity changes (E) are not the major mechanism of deterioration.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient receiving pilocarpine therapy complains of dim vision in low illumination. Which pharmacologic effect explains this symptom?",o:["Cycloplegia","Persistent mydriasis","Miosis reducing retinal illumination","Corneal edema","Optic nerve ischemia"],a:2,e:"Pilocarpine-induced miosis decreases the amount of light reaching the retina, causing difficulty in dim illumination and night vision.<br><br>Brow ache and accommodative spasm are additional common adverse effects.<br><br>Cycloplegia (A) is caused by antimuscarinic drugs such as atropine. Persistent mydriasis (B) would instead increase retinal illumination.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which ocular drug is most likely to precipitate acute angle-closure glaucoma in a predisposed patient?",o:["Pilocarpine","Phenylephrine","Acetazolamide","Timolol","Dorzolamide"],a:1,e:"Phenylephrine produces mydriasis through alpha-1 adrenergic stimulation. In anatomically narrow angles, dilation may precipitate pupillary block and acute angle closure.<br><br>Hypermetropic elderly patients are especially susceptible. Careful gonioscopic assessment is important before pharmacologic dilation.<br><br>Pilocarpine (A) produces miosis and is actually used therapeutically in angle closure after pressure reduction.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with bacterial endophthalmitis after cataract surgery most urgently requires which route of antibiotic administration?",o:["Oral only","Topical only","Intravitreal","Subcutaneous","Retrobulbar only"],a:2,e:"Intravitreal antibiotics rapidly achieve therapeutic vitreous concentrations and are essential in postoperative bacterial endophthalmitis.<br><br>Delay in treatment may result in irreversible retinal destruction and blindness. Vitrectomy may also be required.<br><br>Topical therapy alone (B) cannot adequately penetrate the vitreous cavity. Retrobulbar injection (E) does not achieve comparable intravitreal drug levels.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient develops severe dry mouth and fatigue after oral acetazolamide therapy. Which additional complication is classically associated with long-term use?",o:["Retinal detachment","Orbital cellulitis","Iris melanoma","Renal calculi","Macular hole"],a:3,e:"Acetazolamide predisposes to renal stone formation because urinary alkalinization promotes calcium phosphate precipitation.<br><br>Paresthesias, gastrointestinal upset, metabolic acidosis, and electrolyte abnormalities are additional important adverse effects.<br><br>Retinal detachment (A) and macular hole (E) are unrelated to carbonic anhydrase inhibition.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with chronic allergic conjunctivitis receives olopatadine eye drops. This drug primarily combines which two actions?",o:["Cycloplegia and anesthesia","Carbonic anhydrase inhibition and miosis","Beta blockade and alpha stimulation","Mast cell stabilization and antihistamine activity","Mydriasis and cycloplegia"],a:3,e:"Olopatadine provides dual action by stabilizing mast cells and blocking histamine receptors, making it highly effective in allergic conjunctivitis.<br><br>It relieves itching, redness, and tearing while reducing recurrent allergic inflammation.<br><br>Cycloplegia (A) and mydriasis (E) are unrelated pharmacologic effects. Carbonic anhydrase inhibition (B) is used in glaucoma therapy instead.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient treated with prostaglandin analogues develops irreversible heterochromia. The mechanism is:",o:["Iris stromal fibrosis","Increased melanin synthesis","Corneal endothelial failure","Lens pigmentation","Retinal hemorrhage"],a:1,e:"Prostaglandin analogues stimulate melanogenesis within iris melanocytes, gradually darkening iris color, particularly in mixed-color irides.<br><br>This cosmetic effect is permanent and should be discussed before therapy initiation.<br><br>Corneal endothelial failure (C) and retinal hemorrhage (E) are not typical prostaglandin analogue complications.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which ocular therapeutic agent is contraindicated in patients with sulfonamide allergy?",o:["Timolol","Dorzolamide","Phenylephrine","Pilocarpine","Atropine"],a:1,e:"Dorzolamide is a topical carbonic anhydrase inhibitor structurally related to sulfonamides and may trigger allergic reactions in susceptible individuals.<br><br>Cross-reactivity is an important exam-tested pharmacology concept.<br><br>Timolol (A) is a beta blocker unrelated to sulfonamide structure. Atropine (E) is an antimuscarinic agent.<br><br><em>(Recall and Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with fungal keratitis is prescribed natamycin eye drops. Natamycin is especially effective against:",o:["Gram-negative bacteria only","Filamentous fungi","Herpes viruses","Acanthamoeba exclusively","Mycobacteria"],a:1,e:"Natamycin is particularly effective against filamentous fungal keratitis caused by Fusarium and Aspergillus species.<br><br>It remains a first-line topical antifungal for superficial filamentous fungal corneal infections.<br><br>Herpes viruses (C) require antiviral therapy. Acanthamoeba (D) requires biguanides or diamidines instead.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient using chronic preserved glaucoma medications develops punctate epithelial erosions and ocular surface disease. Which preservative is most implicated?",o:["Chlorhexidine","Polyethylene glycol","Sodium chloride","Benzalkonium chloride","Carboxymethylcellulose"],a:3,e:"Benzalkonium chloride is a common ophthalmic preservative associated with chronic ocular surface toxicity, tear film instability, and epithelial damage.<br><br>Patients on multiple long-term glaucoma drops are especially vulnerable. Preservative-free formulations may improve symptoms.<br><br>Polyethylene glycol (B) and carboxymethylcellulose (E) are lubricating agents rather than toxic preservatives.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with severe postoperative inflammation after cataract surgery is prescribed topical prednisolone acetate. Which pharmacologic property makes this preparation especially effective?",o:["Poor corneal penetration","Carbonic anhydrase inhibition","Strong cycloplegic action","High intraocular penetration","Corneal anesthetic effect"],a:3,e:"Prednisolone acetate penetrates the cornea effectively and achieves therapeutic intraocular anti-inflammatory concentrations, making it highly useful after intraocular surgery.<br><br>It is widely used in uveitis and postoperative inflammation management.<br><br>Cycloplegia (C) requires antimuscarinic agents. Carbonic anhydrase inhibition (B) lowers aqueous production instead.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with chronic glaucoma on pilocarpine develops progressive myopia. Which mechanism explains this change?",o:["Lens opacification","Retinal edema","Corneal thinning","Ciliary muscle spasm increasing lens curvature","Vitreous contraction"],a:3,e:"Pilocarpine stimulates ciliary muscle contraction, increasing lens convexity and producing accommodative spasm with transient myopic shift.<br><br>This effect may significantly impair distance vision, especially in younger patients.<br><br>Lens opacification (A) causes cataract rather than pharmacologic myopic shift. Corneal thinning (C) is unrelated.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with acute retinal necrosis syndrome is most appropriately treated initially with:",o:["Topical antibiotics only","Systemic antiviral therapy","Cycloplegics alone","Carbonic anhydrase inhibitors","Artificial tears only"],a:1,e:"Acute retinal necrosis is a fulminant herpetic retinitis requiring urgent systemic antiviral therapy such as intravenous acyclovir.<br><br>Rapid progression and retinal detachment are major complications if treatment is delayed.<br><br>Artificial tears (E) and cycloplegics alone (C) are grossly inadequate for this necrotizing viral retinal disease.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which glaucoma medication most commonly causes eyelash hypertrichosis?",o:["Timolol","Acetazolamide","Latanoprost","Brimonidine","Dorzolamide"],a:2,e:"Prostaglandin analogues such as latanoprost commonly stimulate eyelash growth and thickening, a side effect later utilized cosmetically in some products.<br><br>Iris pigmentation and conjunctival hyperemia are additional high-yield adverse effects.<br><br>Timolol (A) produces beta-blocker side effects rather than cosmetic periocular changes.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient develops toxic keratopathy after chronic unsupervised use of topical anesthetic drops. The most severe potential complication is:",o:["Episcleritis","Retinal detachment","Acute cataract","Corneal perforation","Optic neuritis"],a:3,e:"Chronic abuse of topical anesthetics causes profound corneal epithelial toxicity, stromal necrosis, neurotrophic keratopathy, and possible corneal perforation.<br><br>Patients may paradoxically continue using drops because temporary analgesia masks progressive tissue destruction.<br><br>Retinal detachment (B) and optic neuritis (E) are unrelated complications of topical anesthetic toxicity.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 70-year-old man with chronic open-angle glaucoma and ischemic heart disease develops recurrent episodes of syncope after starting a new topical ocular medication. Pulse rate is 42/min. Which drug is most likely responsible?",o:["Pilocarpine","Latanoprost","Timolol","Phenylephrine","Tropicamide"],a:2,e:"Timolol is a non-selective topical beta blocker that may undergo systemic absorption through the nasolacrimal system and produce significant cardiovascular side effects.<br><br>Bradycardia, hypotension, heart block, fatigue, depression, and syncope are important adverse effects frequently tested in<br><br>Pilocarpine (A) mainly causes accommodative spasm and miosis. Phenylephrine (D) may increase blood pressure rather than causing bradyarrhythmias. Tropicamide (E) produces transient mydriasis and cycloplegia.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient receiving chronic prostaglandin analogue therapy develops deepening of the upper eyelid sulcus and periocular fat atrophy. Which drug class is responsible?",o:["Carbonic anhydrase inhibitors","Alpha agonists","Beta blockers","Prostaglandin analogues","Cycloplegics"],a:3,e:"Prostaglandin-associated periorbitopathy is a recognized complication of chronic prostaglandin analogue therapy such as latanoprost or bimatoprost.<br><br>Patients may develop deep superior sulcus, enophthalmos-like appearance, periocular fat atrophy, and eyelash changes. Recognition is important because these changes may become cosmetically significant.<br><br>Beta blockers (C) commonly produce cardiopulmonary side effects rather than orbital fat atrophy. Cycloplegics (E) mainly affect accommodation and pupillary size.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with fungal keratitis due to Fusarium species is most appropriately treated initially with:",o:["Oral acyclovir","Intravitreal vancomycin","Topical atropine only","Topical natamycin","Timolol eye drops"],a:3,e:"Natamycin is considered first-line topical therapy for filamentous fungal keratitis, especially Fusarium infections.<br><br>These ulcers often follow trauma with vegetative matter and may progress rapidly to stromal melting or perforation. Early diagnosis and prolonged therapy are essential.<br><br>Acyclovir (A) is used for herpetic disease. Vancomycin (B) primarily targets gram-positive bacterial infections rather than filamentous fungi.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient develops severe ocular irritation and punctate epithelial erosions after chronic use of multiple preserved glaucoma medications. Which preservative is most implicated?",o:["Sodium hyaluronate","Carboxymethylcellulose","Benzalkonium chloride","Polyvinyl alcohol","Hydroxypropyl methylcellulose"],a:2,e:"Benzalkonium chloride is the most widely used ophthalmic preservative and is strongly associated with ocular surface toxicity during chronic therapy.<br><br>It disrupts tear film stability and damages epithelial cells, leading to dry eye symptoms, punctate keratopathy, and chronic conjunctival inflammation.<br><br>Carboxymethylcellulose (B) and hydroxypropyl methylcellulose (E) are lubricants rather than toxic preservatives. Sodium hyaluronate (A) is also used therapeutically in dry eye disease.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A 58-year-old diabetic patient undergoes cataract surgery and is started on postoperative topical prednisolone acetate. Two weeks later he develops blurred vision and elevated intraocular pressure. Which mechanism best explains this complication?",o:["Steroid-induced trabecular outflow resistance","Retinal artery occlusion","Ciliary body shutdown","Excess tear production","Vitreous liquefaction"],a:0,e:"Corticosteroids alter trabecular meshwork extracellular matrix metabolism, increasing resistance to aqueous outflow and producing steroid-induced glaucoma.<br><br>Steroid responders, diabetics, and glaucoma patients are particularly vulnerable. Regular IOP monitoring is essential during postoperative steroid therapy.<br><br>Ciliary body shutdown (C) generally lowers intraocular pressure rather than elevating it. Tear production abnormalities (D) and vitreous changes (E) do not explain steroid glaucoma.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which ocular medication is most likely to cause a bitter metallic taste after instillation?",o:["Dorzolamide","Tropicamide","Phenylephrine","Pilocarpine","Prednisolone acetate"],a:0,e:"Dorzolamide commonly produces a bitter metallic taste because of nasolacrimal drainage into the oropharynx after topical administration.<br><br>Punctal occlusion may reduce systemic absorption and unpleasant taste sensation. Local irritation and allergy are additional side effects.<br><br>Phenylephrine (C) mainly causes adrenergic effects such as hypertension or mydriasis. Pilocarpine (D) produces brow ache and accommodative spasm.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with severe postoperative endophthalmitis after intravitreal injection is most appropriately managed with:",o:["Artificial tears only","Topical antihistamines","Intravitreal antibiotics","Cycloplegics alone","Oral acetazolamide only"],a:2,e:"Intravitreal antibiotics achieve immediate therapeutic vitreous concentrations and are essential in bacterial endophthalmitis management.<br><br>Delay in treatment may rapidly lead to irreversible retinal damage and blindness. Vitrectomy may also be indicated depending on severity.<br><br>Cycloplegics (D) may provide comfort but are inadequate as sole therapy. Artificial tears (A) have no role in severe intraocular infection.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with acute angle-closure glaucoma receives pilocarpine after initial pressure lowering. Pilocarpine lowers intraocular pressure mainly by:",o:["Decreasing aqueous secretion","Osmotic dehydration of vitreous","Increasing uveoscleral outflow","Opening trabecular meshwork via ciliary muscle contraction","Blocking beta receptors"],a:3,e:"Pilocarpine stimulates muscarinic receptors causing ciliary muscle contraction, which mechanically opens the trabecular meshwork and enhances aqueous drainage.<br><br>It also produces miosis, relieving pupillary block in angle closure after initial pressure reduction.<br><br>Timolol-like beta blockade (E) decreases aqueous production instead. Prostaglandin analogues (C) primarily increase uveoscleral outflow.<br><br><em>(Recall and Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient using atropine eye drops most likely develops which visual complaint?",o:["Night blindness only","Diplopia due to muscle paralysis","Central scotoma","Difficulty with near vision","Color blindness"],a:3,e:"Atropine produces cycloplegia by paralyzing the ciliary muscle, thereby abolishing accommodation and impairing near focusing.<br><br>Patients commonly complain of blurred near vision and photophobia due to prolonged mydriasis.<br><br>Color blindness (E) and central scotoma (C) suggest retinal or optic nerve pathology rather than antimuscarinic pharmacologic effects.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with severe allergic conjunctivitis receives topical olopatadine. Which additional pharmacologic effect besides antihistamine activity contributes to its efficacy?",o:["Carbonic anhydrase inhibition","Cycloplegia","Mast cell stabilization","Alpha blockade","Beta stimulation"],a:2,e:"Olopatadine acts both as an antihistamine and mast cell stabilizer, reducing mediator release and allergic inflammation recurrence.<br><br>This dual action makes it highly effective in chronic allergic conjunctivitis and vernal keratoconjunctivitis.<br><br>Carbonic anhydrase inhibition (A) is relevant in glaucoma therapy. Cycloplegia (B) is produced by antimuscarinic agents instead.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with herpetic stromal keratitis is prescribed topical steroids only after initiation of antiviral therapy because steroids:",o:["Increase aqueous humor production","Cause retinal detachment","Prevent epithelial healing immediately","Promote uncontrolled viral replication if used alone","Produce optic neuritis"],a:3,e:"Topical steroids suppress corneal immune defense and may worsen active herpetic epithelial infection if antiviral coverage is absent.<br><br>In stromal keratitis, steroids may still be necessary to suppress immune-mediated stromal inflammation but must be combined with antiviral therapy.<br><br>Retinal detachment (B) and optic neuritis (E) are not the major complications of isolated steroid use in herpetic keratitis.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient develops conjunctival blanching after topical phenylephrine administration. Which receptor stimulation mediates this effect?",o:["Beta-2","Muscarinic","Alpha-1","Dopaminergic","Histaminergic"],a:2,e:"Phenylephrine stimulates alpha-1 adrenergic receptors causing vasoconstriction and mydriasis without cycloplegia.<br><br>Conjunctival blanching is therefore commonly observed after topical instillation.<br><br>Muscarinic stimulation (B) would produce miosis rather than adrenergic vasoconstriction. Beta-2 activation (A) causes bronchodilation and vascular smooth muscle relaxation.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with severe dry eye disease is prescribed preservative-free artificial tears mainly because preservatives:",o:["Increase retinal toxicity","Induce cataract rapidly","Cause vitreous hemorrhage","Damage ocular surface epithelium","Produce retinal detachment"],a:3,e:"Preservatives such as benzalkonium chloride may worsen ocular surface inflammation and epithelial injury in chronic dry eye patients.<br><br>Preservative-free lubricants are preferred in severe or frequent-use dry eye therapy.<br><br>Cataract formation (B) and retinal detachment (E) are unrelated to chronic preservative toxicity. Vitreous hemorrhage (C) does not occur.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient treated with chronic topical corticosteroids develops posterior subcapsular cataract. This cataract subtype most significantly affects:",o:["Peripheral field vision only","Near vision in dim illumination and glare sensitivity","Color discrimination only","Extraocular muscle function","Pupillary reflexes only"],a:1,e:"Posterior subcapsular cataracts disproportionately impair near vision and cause marked glare symptoms, especially in bright light.<br><br>Steroid-induced cataracts classically occur in the posterior subcapsular region and may progress rapidly.<br><br>Extraocular muscle function (D) and pupillary reflexes (E) are generally preserved until advanced disease.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A 63-year-old patient with chronic glaucoma and severe COPD requires pressure-lowering therapy. Which drug is relatively contraindicated?",o:["Latanoprost","Brimonidine","Timolol","Dorzolamide","Acetazolamide"],a:2,e:"Topical timolol may produce systemic beta-blockade causing life-threatening bronchospasm in COPD or asthma patients.<br><br>Even though administered topically, significant systemic absorption occurs through the nasolacrimal mucosa.<br><br>Latanoprost (A) and dorzolamide (D) are generally safer alternatives in obstructive airway disease.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which ocular therapeutic drug is most associated with cystoid macular edema in pseudophakic patients?",o:["Pilocarpine","Tropicamide","Phenylephrine","Prostaglandin analogues","Timolol"],a:3,e:"Prostaglandin analogues may rarely precipitate cystoid macular edema, particularly in aphakic or pseudophakic eyes with compromised blood-retinal barriers.<br><br>This complication is especially important after recent cataract surgery.<br><br>Timolol (E) primarily causes cardiopulmonary side effects. Tropicamide (B) produces transient cycloplegia and mydriasis.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with bacterial keratitis is treated with fortified vancomycin eye drops. Vancomycin is particularly effective against:",o:["Gram-negative organisms only","Acanthamoeba","Fungal pathogens","Gram-positive organisms including MRSA","Herpes viruses"],a:3,e:"Vancomycin provides strong gram-positive coverage including resistant organisms such as MRSA and resistant Staphylococcus species.<br><br>It is commonly used in severe bacterial keratitis and postoperative endophthalmitis protocols.<br><br>Fungal pathogens (C) require antifungal therapy, while herpes viruses (E) require antiviral medications.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient receiving atropine therapy for uveitis develops flushing, dry mouth, fever, and tachycardia. Which syndrome explains these findings?",o:["Cholinergic crisis","Sympathomimetic syndrome","Anticholinergic toxicity","Neuroleptic syndrome","Serotonin syndrome"],a:2,e:"Systemic absorption of atropine may produce anticholinergic toxicity characterized by dry mouth, tachycardia, flushing, fever, confusion, and urinary retention.<br><br>Children are particularly susceptible to systemic toxicity from topical atropine.<br><br>Cholinergic crisis (A) would instead produce salivation, sweating, diarrhea, and miosis.<br><br><em>(Recall and Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with severe vernal keratoconjunctivitis develops shield ulcer formation. Which therapy is most effective for controlling the underlying inflammation?",o:["Topical beta blockers","Osmotic agents","Carbonic anhydrase inhibitors","Mydriatics only","Topical corticosteroids"],a:4,e:"Shield ulcers occur in severe vernal keratoconjunctivitis because of intense allergic inflammation and mechanical trauma from giant papillae.<br><br>Topical corticosteroids are highly effective in suppressing acute severe inflammation, though careful monitoring for glaucoma and cataract is essential.<br><br>Beta blockers (A) and carbonic anhydrase inhibitors (C) are glaucoma medications without significant anti-allergic activity.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient using topical anesthetic drops chronically develops nonhealing epithelial defects and corneal stromal melt. Which mechanism primarily explains this toxicity?",o:["Excess aqueous secretion","Lens epithelial proliferation","Alpha-1 stimulation","Increased retinal metabolism","Corneal nerve toxicity with impaired healing"],a:4,e:"Topical anesthetic abuse damages corneal nerves and epithelial cells, impairing healing and producing neurotrophic keratopathy with stromal melt.<br><br>Because pain is temporarily relieved, patients may continue self-administration despite progressive tissue destruction.<br><br>Retinal metabolism (D) and lens epithelial proliferation (B) are unrelated to topical anesthetic toxicity.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with acute angle-closure glaucoma receives intravenous acetazolamide. Which site is primarily responsible for its pressure-lowering effect?",o:["Trabecular meshwork","Iris sphincter","Non-pigmented ciliary epithelium","Canal of Schlemm","Corneal endothelium"],a:2,e:"Carbonic anhydrase inhibitors suppress bicarbonate formation within the non-pigmented ciliary epithelium, reducing aqueous humor secretion.<br><br>This rapidly lowers intraocular pressure and makes acetazolamide important in acute glaucoma management.<br><br>Trabecular meshwork (A) regulates aqueous outflow rather than production. Iris sphincter (B) mediates pupillary constriction but does not generate aqueous humor.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient treated with long-term topical corticosteroids develops posterior subcapsular cataract. Which mechanism most likely contributes to this complication?",o:["Increased retinal oxidative stress","Retinal ischemia","Vitreous dehydration","Trabecular fibrosis only","Altered lens epithelial metabolism"],a:4,e:"Steroids interfere with lens epithelial cell metabolism and protein homeostasis, resulting in posterior subcapsular cataract formation.<br><br>PSC cataracts significantly impair near vision and produce marked glare symptoms even when relatively small.<br><br>Trabecular fibrosis (D) contributes to steroid glaucoma rather than cataract formation. Retinal ischemia (B) is unrelated.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with severe fungal keratitis unresponsive to natamycin develops deep stromal involvement. Which additional antifungal agent is commonly considered?",o:["Vancomycin","Amphotericin B","Timolol","Atropine","Phenylephrine"],a:1,e:"Amphotericin B is particularly useful in severe fungal keratitis, especially caused by yeast organisms such as Candida.<br><br>Deep stromal involvement may require combined topical, intracameral, or systemic antifungal therapy.<br><br>Vancomycin (A) primarily targets gram-positive bacteria rather than fungal pathogens. Timolol (C) is an antiglaucoma drug.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which glaucoma medication is most strongly associated with nocturnal systemic hypotension and worsening optic nerve perfusion?",o:["Timolol","Latanoprost","Pilocarpine","Tropicamide","Brinzolamide"],a:0,e:"Topical beta blockers may reduce systemic blood pressure and heart rate, potentially worsening nocturnal optic nerve perfusion in glaucoma patients.<br><br>This concern is particularly important in normal-tension glaucoma where vascular compromise contributes to optic neuropathy.<br><br>Latanoprost (B) primarily acts locally with minimal systemic cardiovascular effect. Tropicamide (D) is a mydriatic rather than glaucoma medication.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A 24-year-old woman with recurrent uveitis is started on atropine eye drops. Three days later she develops severe photophobia and inability to read. Which pharmacologic action explains these symptoms?",o:["Alpha stimulation","Beta blockade","Carbonic anhydrase inhibition","Histamine blockade","Cycloplegia and persistent mydriasis"],a:4,e:"Atropine produces prolonged cycloplegia by paralyzing the ciliary muscle and causes sustained pupillary dilation through muscarinic blockade.<br><br>Loss of accommodation impairs near vision, while mydriasis increases retinal light exposure causing photophobia.<br><br>Carbonic anhydrase inhibition (C) lowers aqueous production and does not affect accommodation. Beta blockade (B) mainly influences aqueous secretion and cardiovascular physiology.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient using topical brimonidine develops lethargy and apnea. Which population is particularly susceptible to this complication?",o:["Elderly hypertensive patients only","Infants and young children","Myopic adults","Pseudophakic patients","Contact lens wearers"],a:1,e:"Brimonidine is an alpha-2 agonist capable of crossing the blood-brain barrier and producing CNS depression, apnea, hypotension, and lethargy in young children.<br><br>For this reason, it is contraindicated in infants and used cautiously in pediatric glaucoma.<br><br>Pseudophakia (D) and contact lens wear (E) do not specifically predispose to systemic alpha-2 toxicity.<br><br><em>(Recall and Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which topical medication is most likely to exacerbate dry eye symptoms by reducing aqueous tear production?",o:["Artificial tears","Carboxymethylcellulose","Sodium hyaluronate","Cyclosporine","Timolol"],a:4,e:"Topical beta blockers may reduce tear secretion and worsen ocular surface disease, especially in elderly glaucoma patients already predisposed to dry eye.<br><br>Chronic preserved formulations further aggravate epithelial toxicity and tear film instability.<br><br>Cyclosporine (D) improves tear production by suppressing ocular surface inflammation. Artificial tears (A) and lubricants (B) relieve symptoms instead.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient develops acute retinal necrosis syndrome due to varicella-zoster virus. Which drug is the cornerstone of initial therapy?",o:["Intravenous acyclovir","Topical timolol","Oral acetazolamide","Intravitreal amphotericin","Topical prednisolone alone"],a:0,e:"Acute retinal necrosis is a fulminant herpetic retinitis requiring urgent systemic antiviral therapy, classically intravenous acyclovir.<br><br>Rapid retinal necrosis and vasculitis may lead to retinal detachment and profound vision loss if therapy is delayed.<br><br>Prednisolone alone (E) may worsen uncontrolled viral replication. Amphotericin (D) is an antifungal agent.<br><br><em>(Recall and Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient using prostaglandin analogues develops cystoid macular edema after cataract surgery. Which anatomical barrier was most likely compromised?",o:["Blood-aqueous barrier","Bowman membrane","Corneal endothelial barrier","Vitreous base","Blood-retinal barrier"],a:4,e:"Postoperative disruption of the blood-retinal barrier predisposes pseudophakic patients to prostaglandin-associated cystoid macular edema.<br><br>Inflammatory mediators increase vascular permeability within the macula, producing retinal thickening and visual distortion.<br><br>Blood-aqueous barrier breakdown (A) contributes mainly to anterior segment inflammation rather than CME. Bowman membrane (B) is a corneal structure unrelated to retinal edema.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which ocular therapeutic drug is most associated with corneal endothelial toxicity if accidentally injected intraocularly?",o:["Cefuroxime in toxic doses","Latanoprost","Pilocarpine","Artificial tears","Olopatadine"],a:0,e:"Incorrect intracameral cefuroxime concentration during cataract surgery may produce toxic anterior segment syndrome with severe endothelial damage and corneal edema.<br><br>Medication dilution errors are important preventable surgical complications.<br><br>Artificial tears (D) and olopatadine (E) are not associated with toxic endothelial injury. Pilocarpine (C) primarily affects the iris and ciliary body.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with severe vernal keratoconjunctivitis develops elevated intraocular pressure after repeated steroid use. Which steroid complication is most vision-threatening long term?",o:["Cataract only","Vitreous floaters","Corneal edema","Mydriasis","Steroid-induced glaucoma"],a:4,e:"Steroid-induced glaucoma may silently cause progressive optic nerve damage and irreversible visual field loss if intraocular pressure is not monitored.<br><br>Children with vernal disease receiving repeated steroid courses are particularly vulnerable.<br><br>Posterior subcapsular cataract (A) is also common but surgically treatable, whereas glaucomatous optic neuropathy may be permanent.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with bacterial keratitis due to Pseudomonas aeruginosa is most likely treated with which fortified antibiotic combination?",o:["Natamycin and amphotericin","Vancomycin and cefazolin","Tobramycin and ceftazidime","Acyclovir and ganciclovir","Prednisolone and atropine"],a:2,e:"Pseudomonas keratitis requires aggressive gram-negative coverage using fortified aminoglycosides and antipseudomonal cephalosporins.<br><br>The organism may rapidly cause corneal melting and perforation, particularly in contact lens wearers.<br><br>Natamycin (A) targets fungal pathogens. Vancomycin combinations (B) primarily provide gram-positive coverage.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient treated with chronic topical anesthetic abuse develops neurotrophic keratopathy because the anesthetic primarily damages:",o:["Iris sphincter fibers","Lens epithelium","Trabecular endothelium","Retinal ganglion cells","Corneal sensory nerves"],a:4,e:"Topical anesthetic toxicity damages corneal sensory innervation, impairing epithelial healing and producing neurotrophic keratopathy.<br><br>Because pain sensation diminishes, patients may continue abusive use despite progressive stromal destruction.<br><br>Retinal ganglion cells (D) are not the primary site of anesthetic toxicity. Trabecular endothelium (C) mainly regulates aqueous outflow.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient receiving oral acetazolamide develops paresthesias and hypokalemia. Which renal mechanism contributes to potassium loss?",o:["Increased distal sodium delivery","Reduced glomerular filtration","Direct aldosterone blockade","Increased calcium reabsorption","Reduced bicarbonate excretion"],a:0,e:"Carbonic anhydrase inhibition increases sodium and bicarbonate delivery distally within renal tubules, enhancing potassium loss and producing hypokalemia.<br><br>Paresthesias and metabolic acidosis are additional high-yield adverse effects.<br><br>Aldosterone blockade (C) instead tends to spare potassium. Acetazolamide increases rather than reduces bicarbonate excretion.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with severe fungal endophthalmitis due to Candida albicans is most appropriately treated with intravitreal:",o:["Vancomycin","Amphotericin B","Ceftazidime","Timolol","Phenylephrine"],a:1,e:"Intravitreal amphotericin B is an important treatment option in severe fungal endophthalmitis, particularly Candida infections.<br><br>Systemic antifungal therapy and vitrectomy may also be required depending on disease severity.<br><br>Vancomycin (A) and ceftazidime (C) are antibacterial agents rather than antifungals.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with chronic glaucoma is switched from timolol to betaxolol because betaxolol is relatively selective for:",o:["Alpha-1 receptors","Histamine receptors","Muscarinic receptors","Dopamine receptors","Beta-1 receptors"],a:4,e:"Betaxolol is relatively beta-1 selective and therefore less likely to provoke bronchospasm than non-selective beta blockers such as timolol.<br><br>This makes it useful in glaucoma patients with reactive airway disease, though selectivity is incomplete.<br><br>Alpha-1 stimulation (A) causes mydriasis and vasoconstriction rather than aqueous suppression. Muscarinic receptors (C) mediate pilocarpine effects.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with severe postoperative inflammation after cataract surgery receives topical NSAIDs mainly to prevent:",o:["Retinal detachment","Vitreous hemorrhage","Endophthalmitis","Corneal perforation","Cystoid macular edema"],a:4,e:"Topical NSAIDs inhibit prostaglandin synthesis and are widely used after cataract surgery to reduce postoperative cystoid macular edema risk.<br><br>They are especially valuable in diabetics and complicated surgeries.<br><br>Endophthalmitis (C) prevention primarily requires antisepsis and antibiotics rather than NSAIDs. Retinal detachment (A) is unrelated.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with ocular hypertension is started on latanoprost. The pressure-lowering effect primarily results from increased:",o:["Trabecular resistance","Episcleral venous pressure","Ciliary body shutdown","Corneal permeability","Uveoscleral outflow"],a:4,e:"Prostaglandin analogues remodel extracellular matrix pathways within the ciliary muscle, enhancing uveoscleral aqueous drainage.<br><br>They are among the most effective first-line glaucoma medications because of potent once-daily pressure lowering.<br><br>Trabecular resistance (A) would worsen glaucoma. Increased episcleral venous pressure (B) impairs rather than enhances aqueous drainage.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient receiving topical atropine develops fever, delirium, and flushed dry skin. Which pediatric population is especially vulnerable to this complication?",o:["Teenagers only","Contact lens users","High myopes","Pseudophakic adults","Infants and small children"],a:4,e:"Children are particularly susceptible to systemic atropine toxicity because of lower body weight and enhanced systemic absorption from ocular administration.<br><br>Classic anticholinergic toxicity includes hyperthermia, tachycardia, dry skin, delirium, and urinary retention.<br><br>Myopia (C) and pseudophakia (D) do not specifically predispose to atropine toxicity.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which pharmacologic agent is most likely to worsen active herpetic epithelial keratitis if used without antiviral coverage?",o:["Natamycin","Brimonidine","Dorzolamide","Pilocarpine","Prednisolone acetate"],a:4,e:"Topical corticosteroids suppress immune-mediated viral control and may convert dendritic ulcers into extensive geographic ulcers if antivirals are absent.<br><br>Steroids should therefore never be used alone in active epithelial herpes simplex keratitis.<br><br>Natamycin (A) is an antifungal agent, while dorzolamide (C) lowers aqueous production and does not enhance viral replication.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with primary open-angle glaucoma develops worsening asthma symptoms after topical antiglaucoma therapy. Which drug is most likely responsible according to repeated FCPS Part 1 recalls?",o:["Latanoprost","Timolol","Brimonidine","Dorzolamide","Pilocarpine"],a:1,e:"Timolol is a non-selective beta blocker and is classically contraindicated in asthma and COPD because systemic absorption may precipitate bronchospasm.<br><br>This is among the most frequently repeated pharmacology recalls in FCPS ophthalmology papers because topical ocular drugs still produce systemic adverse effects.<br><br>Latanoprost (A) mainly causes iris pigmentation and eyelash growth. Pilocarpine (E) produces accommodative spasm and miosis rather than bronchospasm.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient using latanoprost for glaucoma notices gradual darkening of iris color. Which mechanism best explains this finding?",o:["Iris stromal fibrosis","Retinal pigment migration","Corneal endothelial pigmentation","Lens epithelial proliferation","Increased melanin production in melanocytes"],a:4,e:"Prostaglandin analogues stimulate melanin synthesis within iris melanocytes, producing irreversible iris darkening, especially in mixed-color irides.<br><br>This cosmetic adverse effect is a classic high-yield FCPS pharmacology topic related to glaucoma therapeutics.<br><br>Retinal pigment migration (B) and corneal endothelial pigmentation (C) do not explain prostaglandin-induced heterochromia. Lens epithelial proliferation (D) is unrelated.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient develops severe corneal toxicity after chronic unsupervised use of topical anesthetic drops. Which complication is most feared?",o:["Acute cataract","Papilledema","Retinal detachment","Vitreous hemorrhage","Corneal perforation"],a:4,e:"Topical anesthetic abuse produces neurotrophic keratopathy, stromal necrosis, persistent epithelial defects, and potentially corneal perforation.<br><br>This is a repeatedly recalled difficult FCPS MCQ because patients often continue using anesthetics due to temporary pain relief despite progressive corneal destruction.<br><br>Retinal detachment (C) and papilledema (B) are unrelated to topical anesthetic toxicity. Acute cataract (A) is not the major complication.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with acute angle-closure glaucoma receives intravenous mannitol. The drug lowers intraocular pressure mainly by:",o:["Decreasing aqueous secretion","Producing miosis","Enhancing trabecular outflow","Blocking beta receptors","Osmotic dehydration of vitreous"],a:4,e:"Mannitol creates an osmotic gradient drawing water from the vitreous into the bloodstream, thereby rapidly lowering intraocular pressure.<br><br>It is particularly useful in acute severe glaucoma where immediate pressure reduction is required before definitive treatment.<br><br>Pilocarpine-like miosis (B) and beta blockade (D) reduce pressure through different mechanisms. Trabecular outflow enhancement (C) is not the primary action of mannitol.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with chronic allergic conjunctivitis receives olopatadine eye drops. Which additional property besides antihistamine activity contributes to efficacy?",o:["Cycloplegia","Beta blockade","Carbonic anhydrase inhibition","Alpha stimulation","Mast cell stabilization"],a:4,e:"Olopatadine has dual activity as both an antihistamine and mast cell stabilizer, making it highly effective in recurrent allergic conjunctivitis.<br><br>This combination reduces itching, redness, and inflammatory mediator release. It is frequently tested in ocular therapeutics MCQs.<br><br>Cycloplegia (A) is produced by antimuscarinic drugs. Carbonic anhydrase inhibition (C) is relevant to glaucoma medications such as dorzolamide.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient receiving prolonged topical corticosteroid therapy develops elevated intraocular pressure. Which structure is primarily affected?",o:["Corneal epithelium","Optic chiasm","Iris dilator muscle","Vitreous cortex","Trabecular meshwork"],a:4,e:"Steroids increase resistance within the trabecular meshwork, impairing aqueous outflow and causing steroid-induced glaucoma.<br><br>This is one of the highest-yield pharmacology concepts repeatedly appearing in FCPS ophthalmology recalls.<br><br>Corneal epithelium (A) is not the major site responsible for steroid-induced ocular hypertension. The optic chiasm (B) is unrelated.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with fungal keratitis caused by Fusarium species is most appropriately treated initially with:",o:["Topical natamycin","Intravitreal vancomycin","Oral acyclovir","Timolol eye drops","Prednisolone alone"],a:0,e:"Natamycin remains first-line therapy for filamentous fungal keratitis including Fusarium infections, especially after vegetative trauma.<br><br>Fungal keratitis is an important<br><br>Vancomycin (B) treats gram-positive bacteria. Acyclovir (C) is antiviral therapy used in herpetic keratitis rather than fungal disease.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with glaucoma treated using pilocarpine complains of headache and inability to see clearly in dim light. Which mechanism best explains these symptoms?",o:["Persistent cycloplegia","Accommodation spasm with miosis","Retinal vasoconstriction","Corneal edema","Vitreous traction"],a:1,e:"Pilocarpine stimulates muscarinic receptors causing ciliary muscle spasm and pupillary constriction.<br><br>Miosis reduces retinal illumination, causing difficulty in dim environments, while accommodative spasm produces brow ache and blurred distance vision.<br><br>Cycloplegia (A) occurs with atropine-like drugs rather than pilocarpine. Corneal edema (D) is not the primary explanation for these symptoms.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with bacterial endophthalmitis after cataract surgery requires immediate therapy. Which route achieves the highest therapeutic intraocular antibiotic concentration?",o:["Oral","Topical","Intravitreal","Subconjunctival","Retrobulbar"],a:2,e:"Intravitreal antibiotic administration bypasses ocular barriers and achieves immediate high therapeutic vitreous concentrations essential for endophthalmitis treatment.<br><br>This principle is repeatedly emphasized in FCPS postoperative ophthalmology recalls because delayed treatment may result in irreversible blindness.<br><br>Topical therapy (B) cannot adequately penetrate the vitreous cavity. Retrobulbar injections (E) do not provide comparable intraocular levels.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which ocular therapeutic drug is most strongly associated with follicular allergic conjunctivitis during chronic use?",o:["Brimonidine","Timolol","Latanoprost","Acetazolamide","Tropicamide"],a:0,e:"Brimonidine commonly produces delayed allergic follicular conjunctivitis characterized by itching, hyperemia, and follicular reaction.<br><br>This adverse effect is repeatedly tested because it often necessitates discontinuation of therapy despite good pressure control.<br><br>Timolol (B) more commonly causes systemic cardiopulmonary side effects. Latanoprost (C) mainly causes iris pigmentation and eyelash changes.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
];